@node MODULEEX "Module Example"

   @{b}Here is a full @{"module" LINK MODULE} example:@{ub}
   
     Example in Assemblee working perfectly with Devpac's compiler :
   
   	beginning:	move.l	#-1,d0		;if someone execute the module :
   			rts			;return to the Workbench
   			
   	Part1:		dc.l	$2407824d	;Part 1 identifior
   	
	version:	dc.b	14		;MultiUsage version to use
	doslib:		dc.l	0		;address for the dos.library
	aslib:		dc.l	0		;        for the asl.library
	intuilib:	dc.l	0		;        for the intuition.libbrary
	internalcmd:	dc.l	0		; address for the internal MultiUsage commands
	fichierdroped:	dc.l	0		; address for the name of the file droped on the MultiUsage appicon 

	Part2:	 	dc.l	$24078243	;Part 2 identifior
	
	Cmdnames:	dc.b	'beepscreen',10
			dc.b	0
			
	Part3:		dc.l	$24078241	;Part 3 identifior
	
	Cmdsaddrs:	dc.l	BeepScreen
			dc.l	0
	
 	Part4:		dc.l	$24078252	;Part 4 identifior
	
	BeepScreen:	move.l	a3,-(a7)	;save a3 for security
			move.l	intuilib(pc),a6
			jsr	-210(a6)	;call OpenWorkbench of the intuition.library
			tst.l	d0
			beq	endBeep
			
			move.l	d0,a0
			jsr	-96(a6)		;DisplayBeep of the intuition.library
			
	endBeep:	move.l	(a7)+,a3
			rts			;return to MultiUsage	


	Compile this example.
	Modify or @{"create a script" LINK CREERSCRIPTS} in s:filetypes and add %beepscreen where you want.
	Load the module with the @{"Cli arguments" LINK CLI}.
	Run the script by dragging the good type of file on MultiUsage app icon : miracle ! The Workbench screen beep !

@endnode

@node MODULE "How to create modules ?"

   @{b}What's a module ?@{ub}
   
     A module is a file containing new @{"MultiUsage commands" LINK CREERSCRIPTS}. So, with the @{"Cli arguments" LINK CLI}, MultiUsage can load a module
   and MultiUsage can evoluate because every body can make their own commands. Attention ! For now, MultUsage is 
   can only load one module.
   
   @{b}How to create modules ?@{ub}
   
     Attention ! To create module, you have to be a good programer with good knowledge of the Amiga's Assemblee.
     
     I don't know very well the C++ so we will just see the creation of modules in Assemblee. For these who know
     C++ very well can make a doc and send it @{"me" LINK AUTEUR} to put it on future versions. Then, I use Devpac
     for compilation so some examples may not work on a different compiler (like PhxAss, ...).
     
     Note 1 : The Assemblee developement is difficult and can do bad things on your machine if you don't program 
     well. I'm not responsable of the damages may do the module and of their contains (virus, texts...)
     
     Note 2 : For now, the using of modules is not very good but you can make powerful modules. In the future versions,
     the making of modules will be much easier and powerful. 
     
     First, a module must an executable file but it must have a specific form.
     A module is divide in four parts : - part containing the module header and some address
     					- part containing the names of the new MultiUsage commands.
     					- part containing the address of the new MultiUsage commands.
     					- part containing the Assemblee routines of the MultiUsage commands.  
     
     Now we will see these 4 parts in details. First, you have to know that all the parts are introduce by identifiors.
     Then, all the parts must be in the same order said before but the first part can begin everywhere. So you can
     put code before the first part and after the last one but this code will not be executed if a command don't go
     in it.
     
       @{b}Part 1 : Module header@{ub}
       
       	  The size of this part is 25 bytes. The goal of this part is to learn MultiUsage which version the module use
       	and it contains five free long words. These long words will be filled when MultiUsage will execute your
       	commands. The words will be filled by 5 address : the dos.library address (opened by MultiUsage), the asl.library
       	the intuition.library,the internal MultiUsage commands and the last one is the address of the name of the
       	file droped.
       	  MultiUsage, to know that this is the first part, search the identifior of this part. The identifior is 
       	  a long word and is equal to $2407824d (in hexadecimal. equivalent to 0x2407824d). So in assemblee, you
       	  have to write : dc.l	$2407824d
       	  Then, you have to put a byte which determine the MultiUsage version to use. For the 1.4 version, you
       	  have to write : dc.b	14
       	  After that, you have to put five blank long words : dcb.l	5,0
       	  It's all ! The first part is made !!!

	  Here this is an example :
          			dc.l	$2407824d	;first part identifior
          			dc.b	14		;MultiUsage version to use : here the 1.4
          	dos_lib:	dc.l	0 		;dos.library address
     		asl_lib:	dc.l	0		;asl.library address
     		intuition_lib:	dc.l	0		;intuition.library address
     		internal_cmds:	dc.l	0		;internal MultiUsage commands address : we will see it after
     		file_droped:	dc.l	0		;file droped address
     		
       @{b}Part 2 : New @{"MultiUsage commands" LINK CREERSCRIPTS} names@{ub}
       
          This part define the names of the new MultiUsage commands what the user will can write in the scripts.
        This part is introduce by the long word : $24078243. Then, there are all the names whithout their %
        and in lower cases. Then, all the names must end by an enter ($0a in Ascii) but when the last name is
        insered, you must put a blank character.  
        
        Example :	dc.l	$24078243		;part 2 identifior
        		dc.b	'hello',10		;name 1
        		dc.b	'bye',10		;name 2
        		dc.b	0			;close the part 2
        			
        	This example define two new commands : %hello and %bye
        	
        NOTE : a name mustn't contain spaces and blank characters.
        
       @{b}Part 3 : Address of the new MultiUsage commands@{ub}
       
          This part define the places in the module of the MultiUsage commands. The address are long words and the
        order of these must be the same as defined in the part 2. The address must be put with : dc.l	label
          This part must begin with $24078241 and must end with a blank long word.
       	  
       	 Example :	dc.l	$24078241		;part 3 identifior
       	 		dc.l	hello_cmd		;address of the hello command
       	 		dc.l	bye_cmd			;address of the bye command
       	 		dc.l	0			;close the part 3
       	 		
       @{b}Part 4 : MultiUsage commands routines@{ub}  
       	
       	  This part is introduce with $24078252. It contains all the routines of the commands and they are executed
       	when a script call them. All the routines must use RTS to return to MultiUsage when the command is finished.
       	Then, you must use PC relative addressing with commands like LEA label(pc),register. If you don't do this,
       	the Amiga will crash !! Be careful !
       	  When MultiUsage jump to your routine, there are some useful values in the registers :
       	  	d0 : contains the state of the current loop. This value is set by the tests commands.
       	  	     If d0=1 : the command have to be executed.
       	  	     Notes : - d0 is a byte
       	  	     	     - if at the end of the command, d0=887667 then the execution of the script will be 
       	  	     	     stopped.
       	  	             
       	  	a0 : contains the current position in the script.
       	  	
       	  	a3 : contains the current position in the AmigaDos command buffer. This buffer is executed at every end
       	  	     of line of the script by the dos command Execute.
       	  	     CAUTION ! This register is retaken by MultiUsage when the routine is finished to be executed.
       	  	     You have to modify his value carrefully and when you call a library routine, be sure it keeps
       	  	     a3 register whereas you have to save it before calling the routine.
        	     
        	a4 : contains the current position in the tests stack.
        	     This stack contains all the states of the loops (1 or 0 in bytes : see d0 register).
        	     
       	 Example :		dc.l	$24078252	;part 4 identifior
       	 	Quit_cmd:	move.l	#887667,d0	;begining of the quit command
       	 			rts			;end of the command
       	 			
       	 		This command stop the execution of the current script.
       	 		
       	 
       	@{b}Accessing  to the internal MultiUsage commands@{ub}
       	
            In the first part, there is the address of the internal MultiUsage commands. This address points to 
          a list of address of the internal commands (like %f, %p, %pr ...).
	    In Assemblee, to execute an internal command, you have to do :
       	  	move.l	internal_cmds(pc),a0	;see the label in the first part
       	  	move.l	$4(a0),a1		;put in a1 the address of the second command.
       	  	jsr	(a1)			;execute the command
       	  	
       	  Notes : when you call an internal command, the execution is made as if you put the command in the script
       	  	  so you have to put the registers given by MultiUsage at the beginning of your routine at this 
       	  	  command. It's very important because all the internals commands use them.
       	          
       	    Here comes the list and offsets (relative to the beginning of the list) of all internal commands :
       	    
       	    	 Offset			  Multiusage command
       	    	   0				%f
       	    	   4				%p
       	    	   8				%fr
       	    	   12				%pr
       	    	   16				%ps
       	    	   20				%fs
       	    	   24				%opencon
       	    	   28				%closecon
       	    	   32				%multifileslabel
       	    	   36				%ifprcanceled
       	    	   40				%else
       	    	   44				%endif
       	    	   48				%iffrcanceled
       	    	   52				%stop
       	    	   56				%request
       	    	   60				%ifrequestchoice
       	    	   
       	    	   
    @{"See a module example" LINK MODULEEX} 	 	  

@endnode

@node LOCALE "How to create locales?"

   @{b}What's a locale ?@{ub}
     
     A locale is a text file which contains the differents MultiUsage messages traducted in an other language than
   the French (MultiUsage is french build-in). To load a locale, you have to specify it in the @{"Cli" LINK CLI}

   @{b}How to create locales ?@{ub}
   
     The locales for MultiUsage v1.4 can be writen by anyone and are freely distribuable but I would like the authors
   of locales to send these at @{"me" LINK AUTEUR} and they will be include in future MultiUsage versions.
     A locale must be write in Ascii but it must respect an order of traducted messages.
     First, a locale must begin with LOML following by the version number of MultiUsage multiply by 10. So, for
   the v1.4, you have to write : LOML14
     Then, all the others lines are the differents MultiUsage messages traducted.
     Note : a message must end by the character @ and can have line return (enter) so the message can take many lines.
      
   The first messages traducted are the 18 @{"error messages" LINK ERREURS} and they are in this order :
   	0  - Error in opening the file s:filetypes
   	1  - Error in memory allocation.
   	2  - Error in opening the asl.library
   	3  - Error in opening the file selector (with the asl.library)
   	4  - Error in opening the path selector
	5  - Error in opening the AppIcon
	6  - Error in loading the icon sys:def_multiusage.
	7  - Error in opening the workbench.library
	8  - Error in opening the icon.library
   	9  - Error in opening the msg port
	10 - Error in opening the intuition.library
	11 - Error in opening the module
   	12 - Error of bad module
	13 - Error of bad module version.
	14 - Error in opening the locale
	15 - Error of bad locale
	16 - Error of bad locale version
	17 - Error in memory allocation for the headers
   	
   Then, after the error messages, there are two messages which are used in the credits window (appear when you
  double clic in the MultiUsage app icon). The first message is the text of the window : caution ! you have just
  to traduct, don't change the author name and the program name !!!!!! The second message is the text of the three
  gadgets of the window. Every text gadgets must be separate by the character |.
  Example : Reload|Ok|Quit : replace the 3 gadgets : Recharger, ok and Quitter (in French)
  
   Then, the two following messages are used for the window which appear when you droped an unknow file type.
  The first message is the window text and the second is the 2 gadgets texts writen like before. 

   Then, the following message is the default title of the file selector.
   And finally, the last message is the default title for the path selector.
   
   @{"See a locale example" LINK LOCALEEX}  
       
@endnode

