@node FEXEMPLE "s:filetypes file example"

    @{b}Here comes a full file example of s:filetypes :@{ub}
    
        This example is installed when you install MultiUsage by the installer program.
    	
    	$lh 4
	%pr#nowrite
	%ifprcanceled	
	%stop
	%else	
	%multifileslabel
	C:lha >con: x %f %ps
	%endif
	@.lzh
	%pr#nowrite
	%ifprcanceled
	%stop
	%else
	%multifileslabel
	c:lha >con: x %f %ps
	%endif
	@.lzx
	%pr#nowrite
	%ifprcanceled
	%stop
	%else
	%multifileslabel
	c:lzx >con: x %f %ps
	%endif
	@.readme
	C:More %f
	@.dms
	%request#"DMS Decrunching...."#"Select a drive...*"#"Df0:"#"Df1:"#"Df2:"#"Df3:"#"Df4:"#"Df5:"
	%ifrequestchoice#1
	c:Dms >con: write %f to df0:
	%endif
	%ifrequestchoice#0
	c:dms >con: write %f to df5:
	%endif
	%ifrequestchoice#5
	c:dms >con: write %f to df4:
	%endif
	%ifrequestchoice#4
	c:dms >con: write %f to df3:
	%endif
	%ifrequestchoice#3
	c:dms >con: write %f to df2:
	%endif
	%ifrequestchoice#2
	c:dms >con: write %f to df1:
	%endif
	@.s
	C:phxass >con: from %f to %fr
	$pk 1
	C:Unzip >con: %f -d %pr
	@.lzx
	c:lzx >con: x %f %pr
	$jfif 7
	c:vt %f 
	$ilbm 9
	c:vt %f
	@.diz
	more %f
	@.bak
	more %f
	@.txt
	c:more %f
	$gif 1
	c:vt %f
	@.snd
	c:dsound -2 -b 100 -o %f
	@.doc
	c:more %f

@endnode

@node EXEMPLE "Full example of types of files"

     @{b}Here comes full examples of types of files which have to be write in s:filetypes :@{ub}

	  Example of lha archives : 
	  
	  	$lh 4
	  	%pr#nowrite
	  	%ifprcanceled
	  	%stop
	  	%endif
	  	%multifileslabel
	  	c:lha >con: x %f %ps
	 
	  Example of jpeg pictures :  
	  
	  	$jfif 7
	  	vt %f
	  	
	  Example of dms archive :
	  
	  	@.dms
	  	%request#"Decrunching Dms..."#"Where you want to decrunch the dms archive ?"#"df0:"#"df1:"#"df2:"#"Aucun"
	  	%ifrequestchoice#0
	  	%stop
	  	%endif
	  	%ifrequestchoice#1
	  	dms >con: write %f to df0:
	  	%endif
	  	%ifrequestchoice#2
	  	dms >con: write %f to df1:
	  	%endif
	  	%ifrequestchoice#3
	  	dms >con: write %f to df2:
	  	%endif
	  	
	  It's all !
	  If you don't understand, see :
	  	@{"How to create a type of file       " LINK CREERFT}
 	  	@{"How to create a script             " LINK CREERSCRIPTS}
 	  	
 	  	@{"See an example of s:filetypes file " LINK FEXEMPLE}
	  
	  
@endnode

@node CREERSCRIPTS "How to create scripts ?"
@{b}
    How to create scripts ?@{ub}
    
    	A script define how a @{"type of file" LINK CREERFT} have to be used by MultiUsage. This script is an AmigaDos
      script but there are also some specific commands which make more powerful these scripts. When you execute an
      AmigaDos command like lha, you have to specify the name of file, the path where to decrunch it ....etc. So
      you have to know what is the file droped in the MultiUsage AppIcon, to open a path selector... In AmigaDos,
      it's impossible know the file droped and the others things so you have to use internal MultiUsage commands :
      the MultiUsage commands.  
      
        A MultiUsage command is always introduced by the character % and the commands can have arguments (=options)
      separated by the character #. Then, on a line, there is only one AmigaDos command but there can be an infinity
      of MultiUsage commands. After, a MultiUsage command is always executed before the AmigaDos commands.
      
        Here comes the list of all MultiUsage commands with an example to understand :
        
             Commands                               Effects
        
        	%f		When this command is executed, %f is replaced by the name of the file droped.

        	%p		Replace %p by the name of the path of the file droped.

        	%fr		Open a file selector and replace %fr by the name of the file selected	

         	%pr		Open a path selector and replace %pr by the name of the path selected.

         	%ps		Replace %ps by the name of the path selected in the last path selector (opened by %pr)	

         	%fs		Remplace %fs par le nom du fichier choisit dans le dernier selecteur de fichiers
         	
         	%opencon	Open a console window to view messages of the AmigaDos commands.
         	
         	%closecon	Close the console window opened by %opencon.
         	
         	%multifileslabel	See the explaination after
         	
          	%stop		Stop the script execution
          	
          	%request	See after 
         	
               Conditional tests : these commands are used to test something and to react in fonction of the result
               of the tests. A loop is always begining by a %if and finished by %endif
               			
               	%ifprcanceled	If the user canceled the last path selector (%pr), the test is right and the loop 
				is executed.
               			
               	%iffrcanceled	Same as %ifprcanceled but for the last file selector.
               	
               	%ifrequestchoice	See the using of %request after.
               	
               	%else		Reverse the state of the loop.	
               	 
               	%endif		Close a loop beginning by a %if command
               	
           CAUTION ! This list is not full, it is possible that there are others commands added by the @{"commands modules" LINK MODULE}
		     created by users. Please see the modules documentations.
               	
           Small example of a script : lha archive
		To decrunch a lha file, you have to write in the Shell : c:lha x <archive> <destination path> so in
	      MultiUsage, you have to write after the @{"string of recognition" LINK CREERFT} of a lha archive this script :
              		lha x %f %pr
              		
              	It's all ! When you will drop the file hello.lha, a path selector will appear, suppose you selected
              system: , MultiUsage will execute this AmigaDos command : lha x hello.lha system:
               	
       
       @{b}* Using of %multifileslabel *@{ub}
       
       		When you drop more than one file of same type on the MultiUsage app icon, MultiUsage run for each file
       	      his script. In the certain case, it's not necessary to retake  the execution of the script from the
       	      beginning, some operations have to be done one time. It's for this tha there is the %multifileslabel
       	      command which create a label where the execution will always retake after it if the type of the next
       	      file is the same as the first.
       	      
       	      Example : lha archive : if you drop three lha files on the AppIcon, with the script made in the previous 
       	      example, MultiUsage will open three path selectors, it's boring ! We have to selected the path once
       	      and to decrunch the archives in this path. So this script has to be write :
       	      		%pr#nowrite
       	      		%multifileslabel
       	      		lha x %f %ps
       	      	Explainations : %pr#nowrite : open a path selector but don't replace %pr by the path selected because
       	      			there is the #nowrite argument (see after)
       	      		       %multifileslabel : create the label.
       	      		       lha %f %ps : decrunch the files droped in the path previously selected.
       	        So, if you drop in one time hello.lha and bye.lha, MultiUsage will ask one time the path where
       	        to decrunch (per example : ram:) and all the files will be decrunched in ram:
       	  	
       	   IMPORTANT NOTE : This label is use if you drop many files at one time ! If you drop files separetely,
       	   		    the label will be erased every time and the script will be executed from the beginning.
       	   		     
       	@{b}* MultiUsage commands arguments *@{ub}
       	
       		Some MultiUsage command can have arguments (or options) which modify the behaviour of the commands.
       	      These arguments are separetely by the character # between the MultiUsage command name and the next
       	      argument.
       	        The commands which acept the arguments are :
       	      
       	      		%pr : #nowrite : don't replace %pr by the path selected but memorise it
     			      #noguillements : %pr put the file selected between " ", this argument prevent this.
     			      #name of the selector : give a name to the path selctor. If the title has got spaces,
     			      			      you have to put it between " "
     			      				    
     			%fr : same arguments as %pr
     			
     			%request : see after
     			
     		Examle of using arguments :
     				%pr#"Destination ?" : Open a path selector with the title : Destination ?
     				%fr#hello#noguillemets : Open a file selector called Hello and don't add " " on the
     							 file name selected. 
     							 
	@{b}* Using of %request *@{ub}
	
		The command %request create a window with gadgets and wait the user to select a gadget. This command
	      make more interactive the scripts. A requester contains minimum 2 gadgets, a text and a title so the
	      %request must have minimum 4 arguments. 
	      
	      Example : %request#"Error !"#"What do you want to do ?"#"Continu"#"Quit"
	      This example open a requester on the Workbench screen and like :
	      
	      			----------------------------------
	      			| Error !                        |
	      			----------------------------------
	      			|     What do you want to do ?   |
	      			|				 |
	      			----------------------------------
	      			| Continu |               | Quit |
	      			----------------------------------
	      			         	
	      NOTE : you can create text on several lines. For this, the charcater * represent the return of line. 		
     	             
     	             Example : %request#"Hello"#"Welcome !*Thanks to use MultiUsage v1.4"#"Ok"#"Quit"
		     The requester like :
     	             
     	             		-------------------------------------
     	             		| Hello		                    |
     	             		-------------------------------------
     	             		|             Welcome !             |
     	             		|   Thanks to use MultiUsage v1.4   |
     	             		|				    |
     	             		-------------------------------------
     	             		| Ok |                       | Quit |
     	             		-------------------------------------
     	         
     	         The command %request won't be useful if there is not a way to test which gadget the user selected.    		
		 With the command %ifrequestchoice, you can test which gadget has been selected. This command
		 takes only one argument : the number of the gadget. The gadget number 0 is  the last on right (the
		 last argument of  the %request command) and then, the others gadgets are count from the left so
		 the first argument on the left is the one, the next one the second ...
		 
     	         Full Example :    %request#"Format"#"Which drive would you want to format ?"#"df0"#"df1"#"Cancel"
     	         		   %ifrequestchoice#0
     	         		   %stop
     	         		   %endif
     	         		   %ifrequestchoice#1
     	         		   format drive df0: name example ffs noicon
     	         		   %endif
     	         		   %ifrequestchoice#2
     	         		   format drive df1: name example ffs noicon
     	         		   %endif
     	         		   
     	     		Effects : First, this requester appear :
     	     		
     	     			--------------------------------------------
	      			| Format                                   |
	      			--------------------------------------------
	      			|   Which drive would you want to format ? |
	      			|				           |
	      			--------------------------------------------
	      			| df0 |            | df1 |        | Cancel |
	      			--------------------------------------------
	      			
	      			If the user select df0, the drive df0 will be format
	      			If the user select df1, the drive df1 will be format
	      			If the user select cancel, nothing is made.
	      			
	      			
	      			
	@{"See full examples of types of files  " LINK EXEMPLE}
	@{"See a full s:filetypes example       " LINK FEXEMPLE}
	@{"How to create modules ?              " LINK MODULE}
     			      				    
     			      				    
@endnode

@node CREERFT "How to create types of files ?"
@{b}
    How to create types of files ?@{ub}
    
    	MultiUsage use two ways to recognize a file : by his name or by it's containing.
    	All the types of files are writen in a Ascii file : s:filetypes
    	The template of a type is :	<string for the name recognition >
					<and/or header for the containing recognition>
					< script to execute for this type of file
					  ....
						>
					Next type ...       							
      
      @{b}1. Recognition by the name@{ub}
      
        To recognize a file by his name, MultiUsage search a string in the name. If MultiUsage finds the string,
      the file is recognize. To define this string, you have to write the string to find introduced by the character @
      
      	Examples : - a lha archive always finish by .lha so you have to write : @.lha
      		   - a protracker module begins by mod. so yo have to write : @mod.
      		   
      		So, if you drop the file hello.lha on  the MultiUsage AppIcon, it will be recognize and his @{"script" LINK CREERSCRIPTS}
      		will be executed.
      		
      @{b}2. Recognition by containing (headers)@{ub}
      
        To recognize a file, MultiUsage can analyse its  contain to identify it. For the identification, MultiUsage
      search a string at a certain position in the file. This string is always introduce by the character $ following
      by the string to find and the position of it.
      
      	Example : - A lha archive contains the string LH at the fourth characters, so you write : $LH 4
      	
      		So, if you drop a lha archive without .lha in his name, MultiUsage will always recognize it.
      	
      	@{"How to create scripts ?                   " LINK CREERSCRIPTS}
      	@{"See full examples of types of files       " LINK EXEMPLE}
      	@{"See a full s:filetypes example.           " LINK FEXEMPLE}
      
@endnode

@node ERREURS "Error Messages"

  Here comes the list of the differents error messages which MultiUsage can return (the option @{"Quiet" LINK CLI} don't have to
  be set) without using of @{"locales" LINK LOCALE}
  
  Message n°      	              Message					 		Why
     0		Impossibilité d'ouvrir le fichier s:filetypes !			MultiUsage don't find the file
     										containing the types of files
  	   									
     1		Impossibilité d'allouer de la mémoire.Mémoire insufisante ?	Not enough memory
     
     2		Impossibilité d'ouvrir la library Asl.library			Asl.library is not in Libs:
     										
     3		Impossibilité de creer un selecteur de fichier			Cannot create a file selector
     										
     4		Impossibilité de creer un selecteur de repertoire		Cannot create a path selector
     										
     5		Impossibilité de creer l'AppIcon				Cannot create the MultiUsage AppIcon.
     										If you run MultiUsage by the
     										startup-sequence, a bug of the
     										Workbench make that if the Workbench
     										is not fully loaded, the AppIcon
     										cannot be create.

     6		Impossibilité d'ouvrir l'icone Env:sys/def_MultiUsage !		MultiUsage don't find his icon.
     
     7		Impossibilité d'ouvrir la library Workbench.library		The Workbench.library cannot be openened
     							
     8		Impossibilité d'ouvrir la library Icon.library			The icon.library cannot be opened
					
     9 		Impossibilité de creer le MsgPort !				The Exec.library cannot open the msg port
     										
     10		Impossibilité d'ouvrir l'intuition.library			The intuition.library cannot be opened
     										
     11		Impossibilité d'ouvrir le fichier module !			The @{"module" LINK MODULE} loaded with the @{"CLI" LINK CLI}
     										doesn't exist.
     										
     12		Mauvais module !						The module is not for MultiUsage
     										
     13		Le module requiert une version plus récente de MultiUsage	The @{"module" LINK MODULE} is not made for 
     										current version of MultiUsage
     										
     14		Impossibilité d'ouvrir la locale !				The @{"locale" LINK LOCALE} doesn't exist									
     							
     15		La Locale est incorecte						The @{"Locale" LINK LOCALE} is not for MultiUsage
     										
     16		La Locale n'est pas faite pour cette version de MultiUsage	The @{"Locale" LINK LOCALE} is not made for this
     										current version of MultiUsage
     										
     17		Impossibilté d'ouvrir la banque pour les headers.		The memory for the @{"headers" LINK CREERFT} hasn't
										be allocated. Not enough memory ?

@endnode

@node CLI "Cli Arguments"

	MultiUsage can have these arguments in the Cli :
	
		locale <name of the locale file> : Define the @{"locale" LINK LOCALE} to use.
		
		filetypes <name of the filetypes file> : change the name of the file which contains filetypes
							(default is s:filetypes)
							
		module <name of the module file> : load a @{"module" LINK MODULE}. Only one module can be loaded.
						
		quiet : MultiUsage doesn't display @{"error messages" LINK ERREURS}
		
		
	Example : MultiUsage quiet locale=ram:english module ram:module
		=> Don't display the error messages
		=> Load the locale ram:english
		=> Load the module ram:module
		
@endnode
		

@node RESOURCES "What are the MultiUsage requierements ?"

	MultiUsage v1.4 requierements:
		- Amiga
		- Workbench 2.0+
		- Small memory (minimum 50 Kb !)
		- Asl.library (I don't know which version)
	
	It's all !
	
	MultiUsage has been tested on :
		- Amiga 1200
		- Blizard PPC 603e 166Mhz + 25 Mb
		- Hard Disk : 4.3 Gb
		- Cd Drive x4
		- Workbench 3.1
		- Roms 3.1
	No problems has been founded.
	
	If you have problems on your machine, send me the @{"bugs" LINK BUGS} 
	
@endnode

@node COMMENT "How to use MultiUsage ?"

     When you launch MultiUsage, if there aren't @{"problems" LINK ERREURS}, an app icon called MultiUsage_v1.4 must appear on the
  Workbench screen. MultiUsage, to treat a file, you have to drop the desired file on the app icon and if the type
  of the file is recognize, MultiUsage  will automatiquelly call all the right programs for this type of file. For
  this, MultiUsage execute scripts defined in the file S:filetypes which contains the scripts and the types of files.
  S:Filetypes must be written in Ascii with programs like Ed,GoldEd ...
  
    To quit MultiUsage, you have to double clic on the MultiUsage app icon and to select Quit. If you select,
  Reload, all the modifications of s:filetypes will be taken.
     
     @{"Create a type of file          " LINK CREERFT}
     @{"Create a script                " LINK CREERSCRIPTS}
     @{"See a full S:FileTypes example " LINK FEXEMPLE}
     
@endnode

@node INSTALLER "How to install MultiUsage on the hard disk ?"

	To install MultiUsage without difficulties, just launch the installer program and follow the instructions
    on the screen.
    
    	If you want to install it by hands, do this :
    		- Copy the file s/filetypes in S:
    		- Copy the file locale/MUEnglish to locale:
    		- Copy MultiUsage in C:
    	It's all ! 
    	
    	To launch MultiUsage on the boot up, add at the end of your Startup-sequence :
    		Run >nil: C:MultiUsage locale=locale/MUEnglish
    		
@endnode



@node QUOI "What's MultiUsage ?"
@{b}

    What's MultiUsage ?

@{ub}
    MultiUsage is a software for the Workbench which can manipulate files with teirs types. So, an lha archive
    will not be treated with the same manner as a Iff picture. The goal of MultiUsage is to call all the softwares
    needed by a type of file easily because you have just to drop files on an app icon and MultiUsage do all the
    things.

@endnode
